    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Online Mediation</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>University of Massachusetts Center for Information Technology and Dispute Resolution director and SquareTrade.com consultant Ethan Katsh letter on August 20 article describes dispute resolution services provided by SquareTrade.com (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''If a Transaction Goes Sour, Where Do You Turn?'' (Aug. 20), which looked at disputes between buyers and sellers over articles sold through eBay:</p>
        <p>EBay does provide a place to turn, in a link to SquareTrade.com, a service that has designed online tools to resolve online disputes. One free tool lets the parties communicate with each other; help from an online mediator is available for $15.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''If a Transaction Goes Sour, Where Do You Turn?'' (Aug. 20), which looked at disputes between buyers and sellers over articles sold through eBay:</p>
        <p>EBay does provide a place to turn, in a link to SquareTrade.com, a service that has designed online tools to resolve online disputes. One free tool lets the parties communicate with each other; help from an online mediator is available for $15.</p>
        <p>Online dispute resolution is easily and cheaply done and is effective and appropriate.</p>
        <p>ETHAN KATSH  Amherst, Mass., Aug. 22</p>
        <p>The writer, a consultant to SquareTrade.com, is director of the Center for Information Technology and Dispute Resolution at the University of Massachusetts at Amherst.</p>
      </block>
